s1 is a String and you are using a StringBuilder to instantiate it which is a different class. Maybe something like this :

    StingBuilder temp = new StringBuilder(&quot;Hello&quot;);
    String s1 = temp.toString();

It has nothing to do with the mutable / immutable properties. 

Check out the [String API](https://docs.oracle.com/en/java/javase/11/docs/api/java.base/java/lang/String.html) and the [StringBuilder API](https://docs.oracle.com/en/java/javase/11/docs/api/java.base/java/lang/StringBuilder.html). They each inherit directly from `Object`. Neither is a subclass of the other. So, as far as the compiler is concerned, `String s1 = new StringBuilder(&quot;Hello&quot;);` makes as much sense as `Dog fido = new Circle (4.7);` 

You could have `String s1 = new StringBuilder (&quot;Hello&quot;).toString ();`. But, that doesn&#39;t really make sense. It creates an anonymous Object, runs its `toString()` method, and then discards the StringBuilder Object. So, why not just have `String s1 = &quot;Hello&quot;;` or `String s1 = new String (&quot;Hello&quot;);` in the first place? 

Note that `String` and `StringBuilder` each implement [`CharSequence`](https://docs.oracle.com/en/java/javase/11/docs/api/java.base/java/lang/CharSequence.html).

The following code will compile: 

        String s1 = new StringBuilder (&quot;Hello&quot;).toString ();
        CharSequence s2 = new String (&quot; World!&quot;);
        CharSequence s3 = new StringBuilder (&quot;Bye&quot;);    
        s3 = s2;
        s2 = s3; 
        s2 = s1; 
  
That would limit the methods of `s2` and `s3` to the methods available in`CharSequence`. If you wanted to use other methods of `String` or `StringBuilder`, you could verify the class using `instanceof`, and then a class cast.

&gt; _&quot;What&#39;s wrong with this statement and why?_
&gt; 
&gt; _String s1 = new StringBuilder(&quot;Hello&quot;); ...&quot;_

The reason that doesn&#39;t work is because _StringBuilder_ is not a subclass of _String_.

You _could_, just append the _toString_ call to the _StringBuilder_.

```java
String s1 = new StringBuilder(&quot;Hello&quot;).toString();
```

