When you encounter something like this, your should put in some print statements to see what is happening.  You can also slow down the process with a sleep statement.
```
public class Loops {
    public static void main(String args[]) {
        int i = 1;
        while (i&lt;=9){
            try {
              Thread.sleep(1000); // sleep for 1 second between iterations.
            } catch(InterruptedException e) {}
        
            System.out.printf(&quot;Checking if %d == 3%n&quot;, i); 
           
            if (i==3){
                continue;
            }
            
            System.out.println(i);
            i++;
            
        }
}
```
prints
```
Checking if 1 == 3
1
Checking if 2 == 3
2
Checking if 3 == 3
Checking if 3 == 3
Checking if 3 == 3
Checking if 3 == 3
Checking if 3 == 3
Checking if 3 == 3
Checking if 3 == 3
Checking if 3 == 3
...
...
...

```
Notice that `i` will increment until it reaches `3`. Then since `i` now equals `3` it skips to the end of the loop, stuck at `3` forever.  So only `1` and `2` are printed.

Your program enters an _infinite-loop_ when _i_ equals _3_.

Increment _i_ prior to the _continue_ statement.

```java
int i = 1;
while (i&lt;=9){
    if (i==3){
        i++;
        continue;
    }
    System.out.print(i);
    i++;

}
```

