In general, it&#39;s better to use Reactor components here instead of manual loping through connections. For broadcasting it provides `Sinks` with multicast capability.

Create a shared variable (could be withing a separate bean):
    
    val sink = Sinks.many().multicast().onBackpressureBuffer()

Then when you want to broadcast from any connection you just:

    sink.emitNext(msg) { s, r -&gt;
        // process error
    }

(take a look at javadoc https://projectreactor.io/docs/core/release/api/index.html?reactor/core/publisher/FluxSink.html how to handle NON_SERIALIZABLE which you&#39;ll probably have)

And then you connect this sink output to other fluxes to make your outbound. I&#39;m not sure how you can make it with your current bean which just returns a never completing flux, but assume that&#39;s just a temp draft and then the real code would be something like:


    public Flux&lt;Void&gt; apply(NettyInbound inbound, NettyOutbound outbound) {
        Flux responses = inbound.flatMap { 
            // your main logic, response to incoming requests, produce new, etc.
        };
        // you would probably want a takeUntil / takeWhile to make sure it doesn&#39;t keep half-closed connections, though I guess Netty takes care of it too
        Flux broadcast = sink.asFlux();

        outbound.send(Flux.merge(responses, broadcast))
                    .then();
    }

